That he remem- bers well that Clanronald made his father give up the red book to James Macpherson from Badenoch3 that it was near as thick as a Bible, but that it was longer and broader‚ though not so thick in the cover. That the parchments and the red book were written in the hand in which the Gaelic used to be written of old both in Scotland and Ire- land before people began to use the English hand in writing Gaelic, and that his father knew well how to read the old hand. That he himself had some of the parchments after his father’s death, but that because he had not been taught to read them, and had no reason to set any value upon them, they were lost. He says that none of his forefathers had the name of Paul, but that there were two of them who were called Cathal.

He says that the red book was not written by one man, but that it was written from age to age by the family of Clau Mhuirich‚ who were preserving and continuing the history of the Macaonalds, and of other heads of Highland Clans.
